Machine Learning for Crime Prevention in Chicago¶

Chicago is an international city, and is a hub for culture, finance, telecom. The city provides a great experience to visitors in the form of natural beauty by virtue of being located along the shores of Lake Michigan, and with landmarks such as Magnificent Mile, Millennium Park, Grant Park, Navy Pier, Art Institute of Chicago, Willis Tower (once the tallest building in the world). The combination of both commerce and tourism made Chicago the second most visited city in America with over 58 million visitors in 2018.

However, the last few years Chicago gained a bad reputation with the crime numbers which are all over the news. To make it worse, most crimes happen during summer when most people plan their vacations to Chicago area. Any approach to predict where and when the crimes happen will be beneficial to the police force with their deployments to potentially stop crimes from happening. Besides the police, Chicago has a lot of community and church organizers who can potentially try to focus their efforts to stop crimes from happening if they knew the locations and times

The goal of this project is to use machine learning techniques to predict when and where the crimes will occur. Since it's virtually impossible to predict the number of crimes on a given day, a supervised binary classification model was used to predict if a certain group of crimes will happen on a given day and in a certain location.

The group of crimes chosen was homicides, weapons violations, robbery and assault since they are closely related to each other. The chicago crime dataset from Kaggle was used, the data contains all the crimes that happened from 2015. In order to train and test the model, the data was separated into violent and non-violent crimes and assigned labels 0 and 1

Data Load and Analysis¶

The chicago crime data set is quite large. This file needs to be downloaded directly from https://www.kaggle.com/armyaviator/chicago-crime-dataset-2001-present

There is a lot of information in crime data, not all of which is useful for prediction. We cannot use use ID, Case Number, Arrest, Description, FBI Code etc. since they all depict occurence of a crime and doesn't serve any purpose in predicting a crime. Other information such as Location (merge of lat/long) is duplicate of the lat/long information that was already provided. Also, information such as Zip Codes, Historical Wards etc. have a lot of empty values and the information can be obtained through other fields

Data Preprocessing¶

Convert Lat/Long into Clusters¶

The districts, beats, police beats, wards etc. are all good way to represent locations, but they are all discrete and we cannot use them to calculate distance for algorithms such as KNN. Latitude and Longitude are very good indicators to figure out the location, but we cannot just calculate distance using them directly.

We are using K-Means clustering algorithm to cluster the Latitude/Longitude, and use clusters instead of using Lat/Long directly.

The number of clusters of 25 is chosen since we have 25 districts.

In [70]:

def plot_crime_incidents(crime_data, incident_type, criteria):
    crime_data = crime_data.loc[(crime_data['X Coordinate']!=0)]
    sns.lmplot('X Coordinate', 
           'Y Coordinate',
           data=crime_data[:],
           fit_reg=False, 
           hue=criteria,
           palette='Set1',
           size=12,
           ci=2,
           scatter_kws={"marker": "D",
                            "s": 10})

    ax = plt.gca()  
    title = incident_type.lower() + 's per ' + criteria + ' since 2015'
    ax.set_title(title)
    plt.tight_layout()

crime_data_to_plot = train_df.loc[(train_df['ViolentCrime'] == 1)]

plot_crime_incidents(crime_data_to_plot, 'Violent Crimes', 'Cluster')

from time import time

def naive_bayes_calculator(matching_records, total_record_count):
    tp = matching_records
    total_records = total_record_count
    fp = total_records - tp
    accuracy = tp/total_records
    recall = tp/(tp+0)
    precision = tp/(tp+fp)
    fscore = (1+0.5**2) * (precision*recall)/(((0.5**2)*precision) + recall)
    
    return (accuracy, fscore)

    # TODO: Fit the learner to the training data using slicing with 'sample_size' using .fit(training_features[:], training_labels[:])
    start = time() # Get start time
    learner = learner.fit(X_train[:sample_size], y_train[:sample_size])
    end = time() # Get end time
    
    # TODO: Calculate the training time
    results['train_time'] = end - start
        
    # TODO: Get the predictions on the test set(X_test),
    #       then get predictions on the first 300 training samples(X_train) using .predict()
    start = time() # Get start time
    predictions_test = learner.predict(X_test)
    predictions_train = learner.predict(X_train[:300])
    end = time() # Get end time
    
    # TODO: Calculate the total prediction time
    results['pred_time'] = end - start
            
    # TODO: Compute accuracy on the first 300 training samples which is y_train[:300]
    results['acc_train'] = accuracy_score(y_train[:300], predictions_train)
        
    # TODO: Compute accuracy on test set using accuracy_score()
    results['acc_test'] = accuracy_score(y_test, predictions_test)
    
    # TODO: Compute F-score on the the first 300 training samples using fbeta_score()
    results['f_train'] = fbeta_score(y_train[:300], predictions_train, 0.5)
        
    # TODO: Compute F-score on the test set which is y_test
    results['f_test'] = fbeta_score(y_test, predictions_test, 0.5)
    
    # Success
    print("{} trained on {} samples.".format(learner.__class__.__name__, sample_size))
        
    # Return the results
    return results

#clf = DecisionTreeClassifier()
#parameters = {'criterion' : ['gini', 'entropy'], 'max_features' : [5,10]}
clf = RandomForestClassifier()
parameters = {'n_estimators' : [25, 50, 100]}

# Make an fbeta_score scoring object using make_scorer()
scorer = make_scorer(fbeta_score, beta=0.5)

# Perform grid search on the classifier using 'scorer' as the scoring method using GridSearchCV()
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(clf, parameters, scoring=scorer)

# Fit the grid search object to the training data and find the optimal parameters using fit()
grid_fit = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Get the estimator
best_clf = grid_fit.best_estimator_

# Make predictions using the unoptimized and model
predictions = (clf.fit(X_train, y_train)).predict(X_test)
best_predictions = best_clf.predict(X_test)

# Report the before-and-afterscores
print("Unoptimized model\n------")
print("Accuracy score on testing data: {:.4f}".format(accuracy_score(y_test, predictions)))
print("F-score on testing data: {:.4f}".format(fbeta_score(y_test, predictions, beta = 0.5)))
print("\nOptimized Model\n------")
print("Final accuracy score on the testing data: {:.4f}".format(accuracy_score(y_test, best_predictions)))
print("Final F-score on the testing data: {:.4f}".format(fbeta_score(y_test, best_predictions, beta = 0.5)))
